.START 

LecTec Corp. said MEI Diversified Inc. proposed to acquire it for stock with a current indicated value of $17.3 million. 

Under the proposal, LecTec holders would receive for each of their common shares 0.88 of a newly issued MEI share.
The Minnetonka, Minn., maker of medical products said it appointed a board committee to consider the bid. 

Investors, who have bid up LecTec shares in recent sessions, apparently found yesterday's announcement something of a letdown.
In national over-the-counter trading, LecTec tumbled 25%, or $1.75 a share, to close at $5.25.
MEI climbed 25 cents to $6.25 in New York Stock Exchange composite trading. 

MEI is a Minneapolis-based processor and distributor of candy, nuts, dried fruit and other bulk food products; its owners include investors Carl R. Pohlad and Irwin R. Jacobs.
MEI, which currently has about 19.2 million common shares outstanding, is seeking to diversify beyond its snack-food interests.
It recently made an unsuccessful $3.3 billion bid to acquire NWA Inc., parent of Northwest Airlines. 

